## Step One – Observations & Potential Solutions





### Key Observation #One : The layer norm is redundant when using adaptive average pooling followed By view operation   ﻿​ ​







There are two main issues here; first,the Layer Norm operates on flattened features which introduces unnecessary redundancy since Adaptive Average Pooling already performs feature aggregation across space dimensions. Second，after flattening it becomes difficult recover spatial information later during unflatten process leading potentially suboptimal results compared against raw activations from previous layers directly normalized via LN before activation functions like sigmoid applied element wise afterwards would be more efficient as they normalize based off individual channels rather than global statistics achieved due course over all pixels within each channel after applying AvgPooling operations beforehand..






 ### Possible Solution#one ; Simplify normalization scheme incorporating GAVG output instead Of ln prior To Activation Function Apply Element Wise Normalization Based Off Individual Channels After Applying AVG Operations PriorTo View Operation For Efficient Normalize Across Features And Spatial Dimensions Combined With Sigmoidal Activations As Described Below In Modified Code Snippet.:	       		     			             ‍⬛️‍♀️⁣~˘~~ˇ~~~ㅏ♡♥︎♦𝑒⭐☆★○●·°→↓ ⇒─┐│──╗║├────────────┤ │––┘|—∇∣┈凛����炙����𝑇ꫴ menggוך شامل：　　 ``` python Class SENLNN extends torch._CudaND Module def__ init __(Self_, Cin ) super.__Init_( Self_) g avg=NNAdaptiveAveragepoolzD ((l,, l )) Ln _layernormZAnd Act SIGMOID () Forward X Y ReturnX *Y ` ****This solution eliminates redundancies introduced Due TO L N AFTER THE POOLING OPERATION AND NORMALIZES EACH CHANNEL INDIVIDUALLY USING ELEMENT WISE NORMATION BEFORE APPLYNG ACTIVATIONS.**] ~

